<!channel> Here are the bios for the speakers who will present this afternoon: Kingsten Banh
I immigrated to Arizona from Vietnam with my family about 10 years ago. Maybe it was my fascination of our interconnected freeways or my dream of creating a legacy for myself, I pursued civil engineering at Arizona State University. During college, I always found ways to do things and challenged the status quo. I graduated after 3 years and realized civil engineer was not a career that I would like to purse as it has many restrictions and required licenses to practice. It was not the vehicle to help me achieve my dream. The time couldn't be any more perfect. Hour of Code was becoming more popular right after my graduation. After spending one hour to code, I realized coding was fun. Programmers are the 21st-century wizards where they control the world under their fingertips. You start out with a blank page and finish with a working program in front of you. The instant gratification of seeing your product immediately that you could not get elsewhere. This is the tipping point of my life where I decided to discard my degree and go pursuing the daunting and unaccredited coding school called Hack Reactor that promises to teach you coding without guaranteeing you a job. After 12-week of immersive learning, I learned how to learn and how to become a thriving software engineer in the sea of talents.


Nick Partridge
I was born and raised, for the most part, in the beautiful land of 10,000 lakes known only as Minnesota. Moved out to Arizona as a teenager which is where I went to college at Arizona State University to receive my Bachelor of Science degree in civil engineering. After graduating from ASU, I went to Purdue University in West Lafayette, Indiana which is where I received my Master of Science degree in Civil/Structural engineering. From there I went off to design structural systems in Chicago Illinois for the structural engineering firm Thornton Tomasetti. After about 2 years of working on amazing projects from Navy Pier Ferris wheel, Wrigley field and Willis tower, I gain a massive wealth of knowledge that I am extremely grateful for, part of that knowledge was the belief that I could do better to automate the structural engineering industry but in order to do that I would need to know the world of computer science. From there I started to teach myself javascript and eventually put all I had on the line and change my life for the better by attending Hack Reactor in San Fransisco. Three arduous months later, I knew 30x what I knew going in and was ready to take on the world and start developing business ideas with Kingsten. After looking around a few places in the valley, I decided to go with Infusionsoft to start my long career as a software engineer.

attachments.title: Understand the Basics of HTTP    - Course by @petejohanson
attachments.text: In this course, we will learn the fundamentals of the Hypertext Transport Protocol (HTTP) by exploring several popular HTTP APIs such as the GitHub API. Starting with the basic structure of an HTTP request and response, we will then delve into the specifics of each element of the request/response messages. Using concrete examples from these APIs, we will cover request methods, response status codes, messages headers, and message bodies. Along the way, you'll learn about specific message headers, such as `Cache-Control`, and `Cookie` and how they control the behavior of clients/browsers and HTTP API services. This course uses HTTPie, if you would like to follow along with the instructor you can download the client [here](<https://httpie.org/>).

Exercise 3 - Collaborating with Github!

Setup

Partner with 2 of your classmates to make a team of 3.
Decide who will be partner #1, #2, and #3.
Part 1

Everyone:

Move out of your animal directory and create a new directory called <your first name>-haiku.
Move into the new directory and initialize a git repo.
Create a new file haiku.txt
Add the file to be tracked and commit with the message ‘created haiku file’.
Open the .txt file in your text editor and write the first line of the haiku. (Make it up! 5 syllables!)
Add, then commit your changes with the message “first line of haiku by [your first name]”
On GitHub, create a repo called <your first name>-haiku.
Add the new GitHub repo as a remote called origin.
Push your local commits up to GitHub.
Confirm that your commits are now on GitHub.
STOP! Make sure your teammates have caught up before moving on to part 2.

Part 2

Partner #1, go to partner #2's gdi-haiku GitHub repo and fork it. Partner #2, do this to partner #3's repo. Partner #3, do it to Partner #1's repo.
Clone the new forked repo (the url should have your username in it) to your computer.
Open your partner’s haiku.txt file and write line 2 of the haiku. (Make it up! 7 syllables!)
Add, then commit the change to your local repo.
Push the change up to GitHub. Your change should now be reflected in your forked repo.
Click the green pull-request button. Review the changes. Click “Create Pull Request”.
Give your pull request a title and (optional) comment. Click “Create Pull Request” to submit a pull-request to you partner.
Congrats! You’ve submitted your first pull-request!

STOP! Make sure your teammates have caught up before moving on to part 3.

Part 3

Go to your gdi-haiku GitHub repo. You should see a pending pull-request from your partner. Review the pull-request and accept it if it looks good to you.
Congrats! You’ve accepted your first pull-request!

STOP! Make sure your teammates have caught up before moving on to part 4.

Part 4

Repeat the steps in Part 2 and Part 3, but this time on your other partner’s repo. Instead of writing the 2nd line of the haiku, you should be writing the 3rd and final line.
When finished, all three partners should a complete haiku, authored with two collaborators.
Nicely done!

Write a function named countToTen with no input parameters that uses console.log() to print the numbers 1 through 10 out to the console, one number per line, no return statement will be necessary. Hint: a for loop could be useful here!

Write a function named vowelCount that takes a string parameter named str as input and logs to the console the number of vowels contained within it. For the sake of this exercise, don’t include the letter ‘y’ as a vowel. Hint: Useful functions here: string.length – gives you the number of characters in the string; string.charAt(i) – gives you the character at position i within the string

Write a function isPrime that takes a positive integer x as input and returns true if the number is a prime number or false if it isn’t. Remember, a number is prime only if it’s divisible by itself and 1. Hint: the modulo (%) operator is useful here!

Write another function primeCount that takes a positive integer n as input and returns the amount of prime numbers between 1 and that number. Use the isPrime function you’ve just created to evaluate along the way!

Write a function power that takes two positive integers as input (n and m) and returns the value of n raised to the mth power. Use the multiply function from the assessment to solve this. Invoke the function once or twice, entering in different values for n and m each time. Hint: a for loop may be useful here!

6. Using a for loop, write a block of code to print multiples of 3 out to the console, with 3 being the first value printed, up to 30. Use the function ```console.log()``` to print the value to the console

7. Adapt the code you wrote in the previous problem to now be a function named ```multiplesOf3``` that takes one parameter ’n’ as input, and prints multiples of three UP TO n * 3. For example, if ```n = 12```, print every multiple of 3 up to 36.

8. Finally, write a function named ```sumM``` that takes one parameter ’m’ as input, and use the accumulator pattern to sum all values between 1 and that number. Once calculated, print the value of the sum out to the console. Ex: when m = 5, the function should print out “15”, which is  the result of 1+2+3+4+5
